      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Was thinking about this some more. IIUC this means we would need to construct an SQL statement and use Query(), instead of using a key directly for Read() or ReadRow(), correct?\n\nno, we can use Read with spanner.Key{InvocationID, TestPath, \"{hash}:\"}.AsPrefix()\n\n\u003e What if we had a key defined as InvocationId, TestPath, VariantDef hash, Id as generated above (randomly or deterministically)? It\u0027s more parts, but I think it would achieve querying row or rows by key instead of SQL, if we care about that.\n\nThe querying would be the same: a prefix key range. \nThe upside is this is a bit more explicit at the Spanner level. But not too much, since this doc explicitly says that ExonerationId starts with a hash\nThe downside is it introduces two ids: the spanner level id (just the random-or-deterministic part) and public id (hash + spanner id). \n\nWDYT?",
